(5 comments)

First and foremost, thanks for working on this. OVA and OVF have been a long-tine requested formats for us to support. Knowing that there's progress on this area just makes me happy.

I'm a bit worried about some parts of this code and I'd like to see those comments addressed. In addition, I believe Ib48c57a80144e865c47829d7e59ce2b3ab3ce5f6 should be integrated here. I don't feel comfortable merging new features w/o tests. not even as follow-up patches. Since there's a patch already, it'd be super cool to have it merged here and be able to review a single patch.

As a more general comment, for the overall Glance community, I'd like to ask what the feeling of extracting, therefore mutating, the original file is. We had a long discussion around this when we were discussing automatic task triggering and, while I understand this patch uses *just* the import task, I do think it falls into that very argument.

The current implementation of this spec is downloading an image from a location, extracting its contents, and then creating a new image out of that process. The original image is not being kept *at all* but its contents.

Please, correct me if I'm viewing this from the wrong angle.

In addition to the above, I think I'd feel more comfortable if the OVF import would be a separate task that could be added to the pipeline just like conversion is.

It's to be explicitly enabled and configured.

Patch Set 7: Code-Review-1

(1 comment)

Flavio,

What comes to mutating original file I have no problem with. The image which we claim to be immutable is being created after we have parsed the OVF container and extracted the data from it. I would have had problem by us creating the image and having task to go and replace the ovf container with disk image and dumping the metadata in.

Also being task that spits out image as a result will help people not to confuse it with image upload process.

That's just my view about the topic 'though. Apart from that I think your concerns are very much in place.

Happy to see this moving, will be even happier to see the concerns addressed and ready to merge.

Patch Set 7:

Flavio, appreciate your careful review.

We have had conflicting recommendations on including the tests in a single patch. We can just as easily include Jakub's tests here.

Further, we plan to pull out the configured properties of interest in a separate conf file called ovf-metadata.conf and a sample will be provided.

It would be nice to capture all properties attached .. but during deployment only the properties the cloud provider is interested in supporting could be used. Should the cloud provider change what they seek to support and we have not the original ova file or captured all of those properties, any changes will be lost for purposes of effect. 

Two ways to tackle this, save the .ovf file in its entirety as a blob with the image. Should the conf file change, then reprocess .ovf file and update the image meta data.But would need to distinguish and  update (add/delete from that conf file set) leaving untouched any other meta data that might have been added through the UI or CLI or via graffiti etc.
A can of wiggly worms of options here!
I am with you on saving the whole .ovf file for future re-processing. Does that address your concern.

To your comment about making it a separate task flow/pipeline like conversion. We are not "modifying" the image. The image is save as is, just the meta data associated with it in the .ovf file is attached with the image. I view this as eliminating a manual step of using cli or ui or something else to specify these once the image is stored.

With respect to some yet unknown format, or random extension but valid image, would like to not support those. ami, vhd etc etc are standard formats, and carry semantics, no need to complicate this.

As far as I see this implementation, everything is done here to bring back the standard workflow if something went wrong. Even in case of error (line 236 in main.py) we just print a message into log without raising an exception.

But I think it'a a wrong approach, because it's easy to find a case, when we will have a corrupted image in store:if file format doesn't match one of the disk formats, then we'll have 'disk' is None, so 'data_iter = disk' (line 176) is not executed. For this reason glance will upload the whole tar file as image.

Definitely I recommend you to raise an exception in 'extract' and handle it correctly in set_image_data. It will prevent the creation of corrupted images.
